MercifulDolls 2023-03-26 6:15 PM
I have a crackpot theory (headcanon? This is absolutely not the intended reading but I like it soooo) about the album and idk where else to put it so forgive me, but: I believe the entire album can be seen as a journey through Adam’s entire career up till now. Hear me out
MercifulDolls 2023-03-26 6:24 PM
Adam, Check Please is obvious. It’s him before even imagining full-time music was a reachable goal- just a skinny kid working at a local Hy-Vee store. Reminiscing on that period of his life and how it helped facilitate where he is today. Under The Circus Lights, to me, is about him first truly falling in love with music, or rather making music. The girl on the trapeze is, in this interpretation, one of his first/biggest influences that got him really hunkering down and making music himself, hence “I knew I’d run away with the circus too” Kelly Time to me is representative of his first few projects and albums. It’s upbeat, it’s quirky, it all revolves around a silly joke only Adam would conceive of writing a song about- it’s the OJ and MID era distilled, in spirit through the eyes of modern Adam. Field Notes is about his sudden success with Fireflies. The gold in the chest is the record deal and his “selling the farm” is him signing and moving on to bigger and better things, so to speak. We’ve seen the darker, ‘saltier’ side of this in Fiji Water, but I like to think this is optimistic Adam reflecting on what a blessing it was in the long term. He can provide for his family and settle down because of that one sudden happening. (As a bit of a side note, I believe the ATBAB and MSS era are captured in the instrumental near the end as a sort of ‘fade out’ moment. Adam does love his movie scores, after all so it’s only fitting.)
3
6:24 PM
Posting this in two parts cuz character limit- sorry it’s so long lmao
MercifulDolls 2023-03-26 6:32 PM
Sons of Thunder is about him slowly getting more open and honest about his beliefs in his music. The lyrics start more vague and interpretive but as the song continues it becomes clear what he’s trying to communicate, until he just flat out tells us. He isn’t gonna hide it anymore for the sake of a label or ratings. The Tornado is, very simply, about Republic pushing him too far and destroying his voice. Something I don’t see people talk about nearly enough is just how DEVASTATING it is for a musical artist to nearly lose their voice like Adam did- especially when it’s as distinctive as his. We all knew his voice for being boyish, clean, smooth- and because of a predatory label he damaged it to the point he needed surgery. I think this song can be seen as a depiction of how that must have felt for him- hence his voice breaking severely in the climax. Thankfully by the end, we see his optimism shining through as always where he tells us that he couldn’t just leave this dream and his family just because of one horrible incident. He was still alive, after all. So, in his own words.. “I kept hangin’ on.” Vitamin Sea might be a little bit of a weird tonal shift but I think it’s very simple- he took a break. He got off social media, stepped away from his main project and just took some time off. Dinosaur Park has struck me on this album as a sort of “return to form”. It feels the most like it could slot into MID with his older vocal style and a simple instrumental. I think this was the point after Mobile Orchestra where he rediscovered his love for imagination and creativity again. Creating his scores and doing side gigs while exploring the world around him. Learn How To Surf is pretty obvious. He’s faced some waves, but he learned how to surf. Just a fun song communicating one of his main philosophies.
6:32 PM
The Meadow Lark and My Muse are, to me, a joint statement on where he is now. He’s reached his happy ending by showing nothing but love and kindness no matter what happened to him. He’s happily married and lives quietly with his wife, sharing songs with us and asking us to listen only if we want to. It’s pretty sweet.

HE am 2023-03-27 7:08 PM
I'm wondering if most of his songs are about him against the label, or if they're more so just his life lessons learned that he wants to share with us, i.e. Meadow Lark is about how we as humans need to understand that we are all just that; people. It's not about us vs. us. As he said at the end of the song "I pray the Lord to guide my ways, With grace to love my enemy". I think the point is just that, we are to love our enemies just as Christ loved us (this comes from 1 John). Then I believe Sons of Thunder to be a Christian anthem that summarizes our hope as believers, that "One day we'll be free, of the various schemes," and "We'll meet [Christ] in the sky" and be with Him forever! To me it's a great reminder of the power we have in Christ through what He's done for us: "You were made to run and not be faint." "So take heart, wild one, for there is a God Who loves you to death, no matter what you've done So don't lose hope 'cause He will lead you home"
3
MercifulDolls
Adam, Check Please is obvious. It’s him before even imagining full-time music was a reachable goal- just a skinny kid working at a local Hy-Vee store. Reminiscing on that period of his life and how it helped facilitate where he is today. Under The Circus Lights, to me, is about him first truly falling in love with music, or rather making music. The girl on the trapeze is, in this interpretation, one of his first/biggest influences that got him really hunkering down and making music himself, hence “I knew I’d run away with the circus too” Kelly Time to me is representative of his first few projects and albums. It’s upbeat, it’s quirky, it all revolves around a silly joke only Adam would conceive of writing a song about- it’s the OJ and MID era distilled, in spirit through the eyes of modern Adam. Field Notes is about his sudden success with Fireflies. The gold in the chest is the record deal and his “selling the farm” is him signing and moving on to bigger and better things, so to speak. We’ve seen the darker, ‘saltier’ side of this in Fiji Water, but I like to think this is optimistic Adam reflecting on what a blessing it was in the long term. He can provide for his family and settle down because of that one sudden happening. (As a bit of a side note, I believe the ATBAB and MSS era are captured in the instrumental near the end as a sort of ‘fade out’ moment. Adam does love his movie scores, after all so it’s only fitting.)
HE am 2023-03-27 7:12 PM

It appears Adam is saying, hey the physical stuff of this earth doesn't matter as much as the things that last beyond this earth.
